{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"12ca5ad6-5cb8-492e-8a4f-68dee4955bb5","content":"Here's the programmatic approach — no guessing, straight from your SDK:\n\n### 1. Find the Android workload manifest\n\n```bash\n# Determine your SDK's manifest band and find the manifest\nDOTNET_ROOT=$(dotnet --info | grep \"Base Path\" | awk '{print $3}' | sed 's|/sdk/.*||')\nSDK_BAND=$(dotnet --version | sed 's/\\([0-9]*\\.[0-9]*\\.[0-9]\\).*/\\100/')\n\n# The manifest lives here:\ncat \"$DOTNET_ROOT/sdk-manifests/$SDK_BAND/microsoft.net.sdk.android/WorkloadManifest.json\"\n```\n\n### 2. Get exact Android SDK requirements from NuGet\n\nThe authoritative source is the `WorkloadDependencies.json` inside the Android SDK NuGet package:\n\n```bash\n# Find the Android SDK pack version from the manifest\nPACK_VERSION=$(dotnet workload search --detail 2>/dev/null || \\\n  grep -r \"microsoft.android.sdk\" \\\n    \"$DOTNET_ROOT/sdk-manifests/$SDK_BAND/microsoft.net.sdk.android/\" \\\n    | grep -oP '\"version\"\\s*:\\s*\"\\K[^\"]+' | head -1)\n\n# Download and inspect the NuGet package\ndotnet nuget download Microsoft.Android.Sdk.Linux --version \"$PACK_VERSION\" -o /tmp/android-sdk-pkg\n# OR extract from your local NuGet cache:\nfind ~/.nuget/packages/microsoft.android.sdk.* -name \"WorkloadDependencies.json\" | head -1 | xargs cat\n```\n\n### 3. Simplest one-liner for CI\n\n```bash\n# Lists installed packs with versions — the android ones tell you the API level\ndotnet workload list\ndotnet android sdk info   # if using .NET 9+\n```\n\n### What `WorkloadDependencies.json` contains\n\nIt specifies the **exact** packages:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"AndroidCommandLineTools\": \"11.0\",\n  \"AndroidSdk.BuildTools\": \"35.0.0\",\n  \"AndroidSdk.Platform\": \"35\",\n  ...\n}\n```\n\n### Recommended CI script\n\n```bash\n#!/bin/bash\n# Dynamically resolve Android SDK deps from the installed workload\nDOTNET_ROOT=$(dirname $(dirname $(which dotnet)))\nSDK_BAND=$(dotnet --version | sed -E 's/([0-9]+\\.[0-9]+\\.[1-9]?)[0-9]{2}.*/\\100/')\n\nMANIFEST_DIR=\"$DOTNET_ROOT/sdk-manifests/$SDK_BAND/microsoft.net.sdk.android\"\n# Extract the Android pack version\nANDROID_VER=$(python3 -c \"\nimport json, glob\nm = json.load(open(glob.glob('$MANIFEST_DIR/WorkloadManifest.json')[0]))\nprint(m['packs']['Microsoft.Android.Sdk.Linux']['version'])\n\")\n\n# Find WorkloadDependencies.json in NuGet cache or restored packs\nDEPS=$(find \"$DOTNET_ROOT/packs\" ~/.nuget -path \"*android*$ANDROID_VER*\" \\\n       -name \"WorkloadDependencies.json\" 2>/dev/null | head -1)\n\n# Parse the required packages\npython3 -c \"\nimport json\ndeps = json.load(open('$DEPS'))\nfor k,v in deps.items():\n    print(f'{k}={v}')\n\"\n```\n\n**Key takeaway:** The source of truth is `WorkloadDependencies.json` bundled inside the `Microsoft.Android.Sdk.*` NuGet package that ships with your workload. Never hardcode versions — always read them from the manifest that matches your installed SDK band.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"51540d8a-d758-4547-b0bf-5b61fd0ace2b","outputTokens":919,"requestId":"E84A:203FDB:267049C:2A8152B:69F93FE6"},"id":"820ca3af-4f9a-4a12-8776-3fe9f7790f25","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:55:20.689Z","parentId":"11770b1a-a1b7-4bf2-b392-ef8f62a6fe6e"}
